
[1]fawn

   FAWN, n. A young deer; a buck or doe of the first year.

   FAWN, v.i. To bring forth a fawn.

   FAWN, v.i. [See Fain.]

   1. To court favor, or show attachment to, by frisking about one; as, a
   dog fawns on his master.

   2. To soothe; to flatter meanly; to blandish; to court servilely; to
   cringe and bow to gain favor; as a fawning favorite or minion.

   My love, forbear to fawn upon their frowns.

              FAWN, n. A servile cringe or bow; mean flattery.
